# What is CSS?

CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) controls how HTML elements look — colors, fonts, spacing and layout.

```css
p {
  color: #1B1F2A;
  font-size: 16px;
}
```

You can attach CSS to HTML in three ways: inline (`style="..."`), internal (a `<style>` block), or external (a linked `.css` file, the recommended approach).

# Selectors

Selectors decide which elements a rule applies to.

```css
/* element selector */
p { color: gray; }

/* class selector */
.highlight { background: yellow; }

/* id selector */
#main-title { font-size: 32px; }
```

:::tip
Prefer classes over IDs for styling — classes can be reused across many elements, IDs should stay unique per page.
:::

# The Box Model

Every HTML element is a rectangular box made of four layers, from the inside out: **content**, **padding**, **border**, and **margin**.

```css
.card {
  padding: 16px;
  border: 1px solid #ccc;
  margin: 12px;
}
```

:::example
```html
<div class="card">Padded and bordered content</div>
```
:::

# Variables and Data Types

Variables store values you can use and change later. Modern JavaScript uses `let` and `const`.

```js
let age = 21;
const name = "Priya";
let isStudent = true;
```

The core primitive types are **String**, **Number**, **Boolean**, **undefined**, and **null**.

:::tip
Use `const` by default, and only switch to `let` when you know a variable's value needs to change.
:::

:::try
```js
let name = "Priya";
let age = 21;
console.log("Name:", name);
console.log("Age:", age);
```
:::

# Conditionals

```js
let score = 82;

if (score >= 90) {
  console.log("Grade: A");
} else if (score >= 75) {
  console.log("Grade: B");
} else {
  console.log("Grade: C");
}
```

:::try
